title: For Sale:  Springfield Model 1884 Trapdoor Cavalry Carbine
location: New Hampshire, New Hampshire, United States
postcontent: This is a very nice Springfield Model 1884 Trapdoor Cavalry Carbine in .45-70. The serial number on this carbine is 452799, which places its date of manufacture in 1887. According to the Springfield Research Service, this serial number is in the range of 1884 Cavalry Carbines issued to A Troop, 1st Nevada Volunteer Cavalry. The lock plate is a Second Type with long eagle wings and smaller shield. The blue is fading to gray with some pitting on the plate. The barrel is turning brown throughout but still has a shiny bore with strong rifling so she should still be a good shooter. The rear sight is the Model 1884 Buffington Sight, 3rd Type, with the "C" Carbine stamp on the base and it functions perfectly. The front sight has the Third Type Carbine Front Sight Blade with the forward slope. This carbine has the Model 1890 Carbine Rear Sight Protector Barrel Band. The Breech Block is a 7th Type and is marked "U.S./MODEL/1884" and has some case color remaining and it is very tight in battery and does not wobble in the open position. The cam has a flat screw replacing the original rivet and functions correctly. Has the original carbine sling bar and swivel ring. The stock is an original Carbine Stock and has the remnant of the Erskine Allen cartouche on the left side. The bottom of the stock has a unit rack number stamp. The trigger guard has turned gray. The butt compartment contains the original Second Type Carbine Jointed Ramrods in excellent condition

title: For Sale/Trade:  VZ.58 Military 7.62x39 D-Technik not Century Arms
postcontent:
vz.58 Military
Imported from Czechoslovakia and manufactured D-Technic. 
- Built on milled receiver
- 7.62x39 caliber and take all standard ammo corrosive and non-corrosive)
- Czech made cold hammer forged chrome lined barrels. 

Advantages of Sa vz. 58 over AK47 rifles (cited from Richard Rich Chris)
- All vz. 58 rifles possess a milled receiver; the vast majority of AK47s utilize stamped sheet metal receivers and are not as rigid as the vz.58 receiver.
- Even with the milled receiver it is almost one pound lighter than a stamped AK47.
- The bolt of the vz. 58 stays open after the last round in the magazine has been fired ‚Äì the shooter immediately knows the firearm is empty and allows for quicker reloads.
- The vz. 58 can be reloaded with stripper clips while the magazine is inserted in the rifle.
- The vz. 58 has a more natural point of aim and is faster handling.
- The safety is more ergonomic making a faster first shot possible with the vz. 58. Unlike the AK safety, the vz. 58 safety can be operated by just a forefinger with the hand remaining on the pistol grip.
- vz.58 has no need for an ejection port dust cover as the receiver is completely enclosed. A cover (on the safety lever) must be used on the AK47 to prevent debris from entering the receiver through the reciprocating charging handle slot.
- The ejection port is HUGE. There is no chance of an empty case getting stuck in the action of the vz. 58.
- The vz. 58 gas piston can be removed or exchanged without tools.
- The alloy magazine of the vz. 58 is half the weight of the steel AK47 magazine.
- The vz. 58 is striker fired unlike the hammer fired AK47. This reduces the number of parts and possible points of failure.

Comes with:

~200 rounds 7.62x39 WPA ammunition
Original bakelite furniture

North Eastern Arms alloy top rail and handguard (with left and under rails)
Israeli FAB Defense pistol grip

Uninstalled Bonesteel Arms nightbreak

Excluded:
Eotech
Magpul AFG
Carry Case

title: For Sale/Trade:  1950's Belgian Fn Mauser .30-06 with Lyman scope!
location: Central New Jersey, New Jersey, United States
postcontent:
I bought this .30-06 rifle last year from a neighbor who had it since his father bought it in the 50's. The gun is in great condition with very minor surface rusting that can be cleaned off and it functions like a dream. The Lyman scope is an All-American 4X scope that has worked beautifully for me. The gun has only been shot around 15 times and only at beer cans and paper set up in the woods of upstate New York and then stored for the rest of its life. The bolt is an FN Mauser that runs very smooth and gives and easy load for each round. The trigger had a great tweak done to it and now sports a little less than a 2lb crisp pull. This baby is an amazing gun to hunt with and can take down almost anything you want but there is quite a kick that comes with it. And as I have been asked a few times, there is no raised cheek piece on the stock, it is flush all around. Not knowing an extreme amount of gun history knowledge, I sought out a few gunsmiths to help find the year of the rifle but the closest I could get between the parts and the serial number is the mid 1950's. The bag it came with is an older soft rifle case but the bolt has torn the fabric on the inside where it sits. I do not want to sell it, but as my taste has changed, so has my choice of firearm and pistols are my new passion. Email me with any questions and offers!  
NOTE: More pictures on request.

title: For Sale/Trade:  SKS owners: Change mags in ¬º the Time!
postcontent:
SKS owners: Change mags in ¬º the Time!

For sale/trade: my modified SKS bolt that lets you change magazines faster and easier. Like - as fast as you can snap one out and snap a new one in! The contouring I've done to the shape of this bolt (after I studied the problem for years and measured and experimented in the shop until I got it right) also eliminates the major cause of most SKS / magazine incompatibility problems ‚Äì the mag lips hitting the bottom of the bolt (which also causes most SKS FTCs and FTEs). 

Open the top cover, slide your bolt out, slide THIS one in, and you'll be able to change mags in seconds without having to wait for ‚Äúlast shot hold open‚Äù or reach inside the bottom of the rifle and lock the bolt open manually with all three hands like you do now. MAJOR improvement in function and reliability over a standard SKS. 

When I finally got this right in my own SKS, jams and stovepipes suddenly stopped happening and I started enjoying my SKS for the first time. 

This bolt has also been torn down, the original (bad design!) firing pin removed, everything that touches ANYTHING burnished and polished (especially the interior of the firing pin channel). Then I threw away the standard firing pin and replaced it with a patented hardened steel MADE IN USA firing pin nestled inside a return spring. Now the pin hits the primer and flies all the way back and doesn't get stuck in the tunnel any more. This eliminates the SKS's weakest link ‚Äì the firing pin which can get rusted and stuck inside the channel, causing FTFs or deadly ‚Äúslam fires‚Äù.  Go ahead ‚Äì pull out your bolt and try to move the firing pin back and forth. You'll see what I mean. One of these days your firing pin is going to stick and when you release the bolt, you accidentally fire a round. SKSs have been known to empty entire magazines without any human help. Scary thought. This makes 1000% improvement in the way the SKS fires.

Replace your bolt with THIS one, set your old bolt aside and never be without a spare.

Please understand that ANY alteration to a default SKS ‚Äì including removing the fixed magazine ‚Äì puts you in the 922(r) compliance arena. Do your own research ‚Äì for instance, a magazine made in the U.S.A. Counts as three (3) 922(r) compliant parts.

And, yes, the new Made in U.S.A. firing pin qualifies as one (1) 922(r) compliant part.

This thing makes mag changes lots easier and faster, and makes the rifle much safer than the way they're shipped over here.

Even with this safer firing pin design, it is still YOUR job to clean your rifle and its parts to prevent rust and the buildup of foreign matter. 

I'm into this bolt and firing pin $120 plus a couple of hours of my time in my shop. What's it worth to transform your SKS into a serious machine that fires round after round without malfunctioning and lets you remove and re-insert mags smooth as silk any time you want as fast as you can pull one out and slap a new one in?

This bolt's my spare. If I sell it, I'll make another. Once you try these two mods, you'll wonder how you got along without them. Even if I don't sell this one, maybe you'll do some research and do it yourself. More power to you. It's all about safety and NOT having a bunch of us yayhoos running around with firearms that don't work when we need 'em to.

If you're interested in this one, shoot me an offer (I'm open to trades, too ‚Äì especially ammo); otherwise I'll just keep it in my spare parts bin.

Stay Safe!

title: For Sale:  K98 German Mauser  8mm bolt action
postcontent: "The rifle appears to be clean, in decent shape and is complete, without missing parts or pieces.  Also, the barrel, receiver, and stock hardware all seem to match.  It even has it's set screws which lock the screws in on the floorplate and trigger guard.  The rifle was manufactured by Gustloff Werke, Weimar, Germany in 1944.  It was captured probably by the Russians late in the war or even after the war.  It doesn't have the typical "X" marking on the receiver like most "Russian captures", but it has all the other indicators.  These rifles ended up being distributed throughout the eastern block countries following the war.  Gustloff Werke, like most arms factories in Germany was said to have used slave labor from concentration camps."  The above statement was given to me by an avid weapon enthusist that is well versed in the K98 rifles.  He is a close family member and doesn't bs or sugarcoat the subject at hand.  I have owned the rifle since around 1998. I've never shot it but it stays oiled and cleaned.  It is being sold with 33 rounds of ammo (possibly more if I run across any more).  I know VT doesn't require a permit to purchase.  I would require the buyer to cover the fees for transfer.  I know a local gunshop that can handle the purchase transfer.
